{"atom_id": "ATOM-SOURCE-20260127-x-article-jaynitx-how_to_solve_hard_problems_by_thinking_backwards-0001", "source_id": "SOURCE-20260127-x-article-jaynitx-how_to_solve_hard_problems_by_thinking_backwards", "category": "claim", "content": "For a long time, the author was obsessed with figuring out how to succeed, reading books, listening to podcasts, making vision boards, and studying successful people.", "line_start": 5, "line_end": 8, "chaperone": {"context_type": "anecdote", "argument_role": "evidence", "tension_vector": [0.0, 0.1, 0.0, 0.1, 0.7, 0.8], "opposes_atom_ids": []}, "extensions": {}}
{"atom_id": "ATOM-SOURCE-20260127-x-article-jaynitx-how_to_solve_hard_problems_by_thinking_backwards-0002", "source_id": "SOURCE-20260127-x-article-jaynitx-how_to_solve_hard_problems_by_thinking_backwards", "category": "claim", "content": "The author made progress in understanding success, but it felt like an uphill battle with frequent setbacks.", "line_start": 10, "line_end": 12, "chaperone": {"context_type": "anecdote", "argument_role": "evidence", "tension_vector": [0.0, 0.1, 0.0, 0.1, 0.1, 0.7], "opposes_atom_ids": []}, "extensions": {}}
{"atom_id": "ATOM-SOURCE-20260127-x-article-jaynitx-how_to_solve_hard_problems_by_thinking_backwards-0003", "source_id": "SOURCE-20260127-x-article-jaynitx-how_to_solve_hard_problems_by_thinking_backwards", "category": "concept", "content": "Charlie Munger's idea of \"Invert, always invert\" suggests that many hard problems are best solved by addressing them backwards.", "line_start": 14, "line_end": 19, "chaperone": {"context_type": "consensus", "argument_role": "claim", "tension_vector": [0.1, 0.6, 0.0, 0.1, 0.7, 0.9], "opposes_atom_ids": []}, "extensions": {}}
{"atom_id": "ATOM-SOURCE-20260127-x-article-jaynitx-how_to_solve_hard_problems_by_thinking_backwards-0004", "source_id": "SOURCE-20260127-x-article-jaynitx-how_to_solve_hard_problems_by_thinking_backwards", "category": "claim", "content": "The author initially dismissed Munger's inversion principle as mere clever wordplay but later realized its profound implications.", "line_start": 21, "line_end": 24, "chaperone": {"context_type": "anecdote", "argument_role": "evidence", "tension_vector": [0.0, 0.1, 0.0, 0.1, 0.1, 0.7], "opposes_atom_ids": []}, "extensions": {}}
{"atom_id": "ATOM-SOURCE-20260127-x-article-jaynitx-how_to_solve_hard_problems_by_thinking_backwards-0005", "source_id": "SOURCE-20260127-x-article-jaynitx-how_to_solve_hard_problems_by_thinking_backwards", "category": "praxis_hook", "content": "Instead of asking \"how do I succeed?\", ask \"how would I guarantee failure?\" and then avoid those things. This applies to building companies, relationships, and other life aspects.", "line_start": 29, "line_end": 37, "chaperone": {"context_type": "method", "argument_role": "claim", "tension_vector": [0.1, 0.5, 0.0, 0.1, 0.9, 0.9], "opposes_atom_ids": []}, "extensions": {}}
{"atom_id": "ATOM-SOURCE-20260127-x-article-jaynitx-how_to_solve_hard_problems_by_thinking_backwards-0006", "source_id": "SOURCE-20260127-x-article-jaynitx-how_to_solve_hard_problems_by_thinking_backwards", "category": "claim", "content": "Charlie Munger stated that a significant long-term advantage comes from consistently trying not to be stupid, rather than trying to be very intelligent.", "line_start": 40, "line_end": 43, "chaperone": {"context_type": "consensus", "argument_role": "claim", "tension_vector": [0.1, 0.7, 0.0, 0.1, 0.6, 0.9], "opposes_atom_ids": []}, "extensions": {}}
{"atom_id": "ATOM-SOURCE-20260127-x-article-jaynitx-how_to_solve_hard_problems_by_thinking_backwards-0007", "source_id": "SOURCE-20260127-x-article-jaynitx-how_to_solve_hard_problems_by_thinking_backwards", "category": "claim", "content": "Most people default to \"forward thinking\" because it feels more productive, leading to brainstorming tactics and making lists, but success has many uncertain paths.", "line_start": 47, "line_end": 53, "chaperone": {"context_type": "consensus", "argument_role": "evidence", "tension_vector": [0.1, 0.4, 0.0, 0.1, 0.2, 0.7], "opposes_atom_ids": []}, "extensions": {}}
{"atom_id": "ATOM-SOURCE-20260127-x-article-jaynitx-how_to_solve_hard_problems_by_thinking_backwards-0008", "source_id": "SOURCE-20260127-x-article-jaynitx-how_to_solve_hard_problems_by_thinking_backwards", "category": "claim", "content": "Failure is more predictable than success, with a relatively small number of common factors reliably leading to negative outcomes in businesses, relationships, health, and careers.", "line_start": 55, "line_end": 60, "chaperone": {"context_type": "consensus", "argument_role": "claim", "tension_vector": [0.1, 0.6, 0.0, 0.6, 0.5, 0.9], "opposes_atom_ids": []}, "extensions": {}}
{"atom_id": "ATOM-SOURCE-20260127-x-article-jaynitx-how_to_solve_hard_problems_by_thinking_backwards-0009", "source_id": "SOURCE-20260127-x-article-jaynitx-how_to_solve_hard_problems_by_thinking_backwards", "category": "claim", "content": "Inversion is powerful because the paths to success are numerous and uncertain, while the paths to failure are few and well-documented.", "line_start": 62, "line_end": 64, "chaperone": {"context_type": "consensus", "argument_role": "claim", "tension_vector": [0.1, 0.6, 0.0, 0.1, 0.5, 0.9], "opposes_atom_ids": []}, "extensions": {}}
{"atom_id": "ATOM-SOURCE-20260127-x-article-jaynitx-how_to_solve_hard_problems_by_thinking_backwards-0010", "source_id": "SOURCE-20260127-x-article-jaynitx-how_to_solve_hard_problems_by_thinking_backwards", "category": "praxis_hook", "content": "Avoiding obvious failure paths provides a significant advantage over most people.", "line_start": 66, "line_end": 66, "chaperone": {"context_type": "method", "argument_role": "claim", "tension_vector": [0.1, 0.5, 0.0, 0.1, 0.8, 0.9], "opposes_atom_ids": []}, "extensions": {}}
